body:
@machristie Thanks for the review. This works for multiple files as well. Have a look at line 197
processOutput.setName(fileName);
Output name is changed for each fetched file name.

@DImuthuUpe the changes look good.

Overall, the code looks good and I can see why this feature is useful, but I have some reservations about this approach and what it means for the data model.  I don't think we should have OutputDataObjectType have DataTypes of STRING, INTEGER or FLOAT. Those DataType only make sense for application inputs, they don't make sense for application outputs. For Airavata, application outputs are only files. Extracting a scalar value from an application output file should be done by a downstream consumer in a workflow instead of directly in the application execution.

However, I'm fine with moving forward with this as a short term solution because, as I said, I can see the value of it.

@ericfranz 
This was published as a package to https://rubygems.org/gems/airavata

Thanks
